# Woodworking Sidekick — Cursor Rules

## Stack
Next.js 15 (App Router), TypeScript strict, Vercel AI SDK, Gemini, Supabase (Postgres + Auth + RLS), Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Zod, Vitest, Playwright

## Conventions
- Use App Router (app/ directory, page.tsx, layout.tsx)
- Server Components by default, "use client" only when interactive
- TypeScript strict mode, no `any` without justification
- Zod for all external data validation (API inputs, LLM outputs)
- Tailwind for styling, shadcn/ui for components
- Store LLM prompt templates in `lib/prompts/` as constants
- Use Vercel AI SDK (`streamText`, `useChat`) — never raw Gemini API calls
- Supabase RLS for data access — never bypass with service key client-side
- Validate every generated plan through `lib/validation/` rules
- Handle errors with error.tsx boundaries

## File Patterns
- Pages and layouts: `app/`
- API route handlers: `app/api/`
- Reusable UI components: `components/`
- Utilities, clients, AI config: `lib/`
- LLM prompt templates: `lib/prompts/`
- Woodworking validation rules: `lib/validation/`
- Shared TypeScript types: `types/`
- Tests mirror source: `tests/`

## Testing
- Framework: Vitest + React Testing Library (unit), Playwright (e2e)
- Write tests FIRST, then implementation
- Mock Gemini API and Supabase in unit tests
- Never mock Zod validation or woodworking dimension logic
- Coverage target: 80%+

## Key Patterns
- Structured JSON plans (WoodworkingPlan schema) — not free text
- Multi-layer validation: Zod → woodworking rules → re-generation on failure
- Tool profile adaptation: plans match user's declared tools
- Wood movement: panels >6" require movement notes
